    "rationale": "This is a canonical example of the Houben-Hoesch reaction, featuring the acylation of a highly activated, electron-rich aromatic ring (1,3,5-trimethoxybenzene) with a simple nitrile (acetonitrile). The reaction is catalyzed by a Lewis acid (ZnCl2) and a Brønsted acid (HCl), followed by aqueous workup (not explicitly shown but implied for imine hydrolysis) to yield the corresponding aryl ketone. This example clearly illustrates the key transformation: the formation of a C(aryl)-C(acyl) bond from an arene and a nitrile.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple, highly activated arene (1,3,5-trimethoxybenzene) and a simple nitrile (acetonitrile). It avoids using phenol itself, which could be confused with Fries or Kolbe-Schmitt reactions. The use of a nitrile as the acylating agent is specific to the Houben-Hoesch reaction and distinguishes it from Friedel-Crafts acylation, which uses acyl halides or anhydrides. The simple, acyclic nature of the reactants minimizes potential overlap with other named reactions involving complex ring systems."
  }
}
